{
  "texts": [
    "Silicon photonic spectrometers for biosensing applications often require an operational wavelength incompatible with the C/L/O bands 154.",
    "This becomes the most significant bottleneck, since new waveguides (vs. the standard 220 nm) and other photonic components have to be designed, tested, and characterized 155.",
    "The lasers are also challenging, and the need for broad wavelength tuning or multiwavelength lasers at these non-standard wavelengths poses severe difficulty.",
    "Finally, the stability and replicability of the measurements are crucial for biosensing applications, and the performance of the PIC and laser has to be maintained despite the environmental drift.",
    "The stability and replicability requirements for evanescent-field biosensors are even more stringent, since an invasive measurement of blood or other bodily fluid increases the user's expectation for trust."
  ]
}